This Signal Processing Grand Challenge (SPGC) focuses on evaluating the cross-task generalization capabilities of sound pre-trained models. Inspired by HEAR benchmark~\cite{turian2022hear}, we extend the task coverage to include a wider range of speech-related tasks and real-world applications, while maintaining the focus on universal sound embedding. Participants will submit models capable of generating fixed-dimensional embedding vectors from audio waveforms. These models will be evaluated on a diverse set of tasks, including speech recognition, sound event detection, music classification, and more. We will use both fine-tuned linear output layers and K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) to assess the models' performance across various tasks, thus evaluating both their adaptability and the quality of extracted features. This challenge aims to push the boundaries of sound representation learning and foster the development of robust, generalizable models for diverse audio applications.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

The rapid advancement in self-supervised learning (SSL) techniques has significantly improved the ability to learn powerful representations from audio data. Notably, models like wav2vec2~\cite{baevski2020wav2vec}, Data2vec~\cite{baevski2022data2vec}, and Dasheng~\cite{dinkel2024dasheng} have demonstrated remarkable performance in various audio-related tasks with limited labeled data. Wav2vec2, for instance, has shown that pre-training on large amounts of unlabeled speech data followed by fine-tuning on a small labeled dataset can outperform traditional semi-supervised methods in speech recognition. Similarly, data2vec introduces a unified approach to self-supervised learning across different modalities, achieving competitive performance in speech, image, and NLP tasks. Dasheng further extends the scope by addressing the generalization gap between speech and other sound domains, such as environmental sounds and music, through a massive SSL audio encoder trained on a diverse audio dataset.

Despite these advancements, there remains a critical need for a comprehensive benchmark to evaluate the generalizability and robustness of audio representation models across a wide range of tasks and domains. The proposed ICASSP 2025 Signal Processing Grand Challenge aims to address this gap by encouraging the development of universal audio representations that perform well across diverse tasks, including speech recognition, environmental sound classification, and music genre classification, among others.

\section{Related Work}

In recent years, several challenges and benchmarks have been proposed to evaluate the generalization ability of audio representations across various tasks. However, there is still a need for a more comprehensive and diverse benchmark that covers a wide range of tasks in speech, environmental sound, and music domains. In this section, we discuss some of the most relevant related work and highlight the unique contributions of our proposed challenge.

\subsection{HEAR: Holistic Evaluation of Audio Representations}
The HEAR benchmark \cite{turian2022hear} aims to develop a general-purpose audio representation that provides a strong basis for learning in a wide variety of tasks and scenarios. HEAR evaluates audio representations using a benchmark suite across speech, environmental sound, and music domains, with tasks involving short and long time spans. The benchmark consists of nineteen diverse tasks, open-source evaluation code, an API for developing HEAR-compatible models, and a leaderboard to track performance.

Our proposed challenge is strongly inspired by HEAR and retains its advantages while introducing several improvements. We include a more diverse set of tasks, particularly focusing on speech-related tasks, which are underrepresented in HEAR. We also remove tasks that are not practical or have small test sets, leading to high variance in results. Additionally, we introduce tasks that reflect real-world applications, such as those related to intelligent car cabins, and provide corresponding datasets. Furthermore, we incorporate a K-Nearest Neighbor (KNN) evaluation method without any training to assess the generalization ability of audio representations. Finally, we propose a more efficient evaluation system based on webdataset, supporting multi-node, multi-GPU execution, and compatibility with slurm.

\subsection{SUPERB: Speech processing Universal PERformance Benchmark}
SUPERBSUPERB \cite{yang2021superb} xxxxxx.

\subsection{DASB - Discrete Audio and Speech Benchmark}
The Discrete Audio and Speech Benchmark (DASB) \cite{mousavi2024dasb} is a comprehensive leaderboard for benchmarking discrete audio tokens across a wide range of discriminative and generative tasks. While discrete representations are important, our challenge does not focus on discretization for several reasons. First, continuous representations are still widely used and have shown strong performance across various tasks. Second, evaluating both discrete and continuous representations would significantly increase the complexity of the challenge and may dilute the focus on the core goal of assessing the generalization ability of audio representations. Finally, we believe that the field of discrete audio representation learning is still in its early stages, and it may be premature to include it as a central component of our challenge.

In conclusion, while there have been several valuable contributions to the evaluation of audio representations, our proposed challenge offers a unique and comprehensive platform for assessing the generalization ability of audio representations across a diverse set of tasks in speech, environmental sound, and music domains. By addressing the limitations of existing benchmarks and introducing novel features, such as real-world application tasks and KNN evaluation, we aim to encourage further research and development in the field of universal audio representation learning.


\section{Challenge Description}

\subsection{Overview}

This challenge focuses on evaluating the generalization capabilities of pre-trained audio models across a diverse set of tasks. Participants are required to submit models that take audio waveforms as input and produce fixed-dimension embedding vector sequences as output. These models will be evaluated on approximately 30 different tasks spanning various audio domains, including speech, music, and environmental sounds.

